That’s a good answer.

“All and none” usually means you’re not pointing at a specific physical system — you’re pointing at the structural pattern underneath them.

So let’s strip away membrane, spacetime, metaphor — and look at the invariant.

⸻

What does it mean to “stretch and oscillate a space”?

There are three clean layers:

1. Stretching = changing the metric

A “space” becomes measurable only once you define a metric:

ds^2 = g_{ij} dx^i dx^j

Stretching means changing g_{ij}.

That changes how distances are computed.

No objects needed. Just geometry.

⸻

2. Oscillating = time-varying metric

Now let the metric depend on time:

g_{ij}(t)

Now lengths, angles, volumes change in time.

The “stage” moves.

This is deeper than vibrating an object.
It’s vibrating the rule that defines measurement.

⸻

3. What happens structurally?

Whenever you allow oscillation in a linear system:

You get:
	•	A Laplacian (second spatial derivative)
	•	A second time derivative
	•	A quadratic energy functional

Waves emerge because restoring forces are proportional to curvature.

Curvature is second order.

So again we land at:

Second-order structure is the minimal stable oscillatory structure.

⸻

Now the deeper invariant

Why does a drum produce modes?
Why do gravitational waves propagate?
Why do quantum fields oscillate?

Because:

Any system with:
	•	Linearity
	•	A conserved quadratic norm
	•	Local interactions

will support wave solutions.

Oscillation is not special.

It is the natural behavior of second-order systems.

⸻

If you “oscillate space itself”

You’re modulating the metric.

That means:

The definition of distance changes in time.

If the change is small → linear waves.
If large → nonlinear mode coupling.
If extreme → topology change.

In general relativity, small oscillations in the metric are gravitational waves.
In condensed matter, oscillating geometry can simulate effective fields.
In math, oscillating a metric changes the spectrum of the Laplacian.

And spectrum is geometry encoded as frequency.

⸻

Why this keeps tying back to squaring

The wave equation comes from minimizing an energy functional like:

E = \int \left( (\partial_t u)^2 + |\nabla u|^2 \right) dx

Both terms are quadratic.

Oscillation requires a quadratic energy well.

No quadratic curvature → no harmonic oscillation.

So again:

Second order is the first layer where measurable structure stabilizes.

⸻

The meta-pattern you’re circling

Stretch → define metric
Oscillate → probe curvature
Spectrum → reveal structure

Oscillation is a diagnostic tool for geometry.

Which is why:
	•	Drums reveal shapes
	•	Spectral lines reveal atoms
	•	Gravitational waves reveal spacetime curvature
	•	Eigenvalues reveal matrix structure

Frequency is geometry translated into time.

⸻

Now I’m going to push one notch deeper, because “all and none” suggests you’re sniffing something abstract.

If space is defined by a quadratic form…

And oscillation probes that quadratic form…

Then the persistent appearance of squares is not about space.

It’s about the fact that reality seems to be built on structures that admit a conserved quadratic norm.

That’s the real invariant.

If that norm didn’t exist, you wouldn’t get stable oscillations.
You wouldn’t get interference.
You wouldn’t get probability conservation.
You wouldn’t get energy conservation.

Quadratic conservation is the quiet backbone.

⸻

Let me ask you something sharp:

Are you exploring whether oscillation is a way to reveal hidden structure…

or whether oscillation might actually be the fundamental thing and “space” is what emerges from stable standing modes?

Those are very different philosophical directions.